<DOC><DOCNO> AP881009-0018 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 1115EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Germany-FreeDemocrats     10-09 0233</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Germany-Free Democrats,0240</SECOND><HEAD>Figure In 1984 Scandal Elected To Head Political Party</HEAD><DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A Prussian count and formereconomics minister convicted last year of tax evasion was electedhead of The Free Democrats, junior partners in West Germany'scoalition government.   Otto Graf Lambsdorff, who resigned as economics minister fouryears ago during a scandal over alleged illegal politicalcontributions by the West German Flick industrial group, won thejob of party chairman Saturday.   He defeated challenger Irmgard Adam-Schwaetzer for the job atthe Free Democrats' national party congress.   In February 1987, a court convicted Lambsdorff of tax evasionand fined him $96,000 but acquitted him on the more serious chargeof corruption in connection with the scandal.   Lambsdorff denied any wrongdoing during his 18-month trial,alleging the charges against him were politically motivated.   The 61-year-old Lambsdorff takes over as the Free Democrats' newchairman from Martin Bangemann, who is West Germany's currenteconomics minister.   Bangemann is resigning as economics minister to take a seat nextyear on the European Economic Community Commission in Brussels.   Ms. Adam-Schwaetzer, 46, a high-ranking official in the WestGerman Foreign Ministry and a protege of Foreign MinisterHans-Dietrich Genscher, received 187 votes to Lambsdorff's 211 inSaturday's voting.   The business-oriented Free Democrats are partners in WestGermany's coalition government, which also includes ChancellorHelmut Kohl's Christian Democrats and the conservative ChristianSocial Union.</TEXT></DOC>